More work is obviously needed but this demonstrate the potential of DNAm clocks as a clinical biomarker that may help with disease management in schizophrenia. Thanks for reading, any feedback is welcome. end/14

Recent studies have shown that the mortality gap between scz and the general population has been increasing over the past decades, further stressing the urgency to find biomarkers that can help identify cases at risk. 13/n

To summarize, DNA methylation clocks are pretty cool tools to study biological aging. We show that we can quantify differential aging in schizophrenia and that we are able to identify patient groups that may be at increased mortality risk. 12/n

There are other interesting results in the manuscript; we for example observe age deceleration with the Horvath clock in cases during early adulthood which we don‚Äôt really have an explanation for. We also breakdown the aging effects by cell type proportions & smoking scores 11/n

This is quite a big effect! A 1-year difference in Levine Œîage is associate with a 9% increase risk of all-cause mortality. Our findings suggest that these female cases who carry high SCZ PRS may be at increased mortality risk. 10/n

We integrated SCZ PRS, age at onset, and illness duration in the model and observed a nonlinear relationship between PRS and differential aging in these women. At the high end of PRS, female cases appear +7 years older than their chronological age compared to matched controls.9/n https://t.co/zxfybiO8QC
Let‚Äôs zoom in on age acceleration with the Levine clock in female cases > 36 years, which is the window with the largest effect explaining 7.7% of the variance in disease status. 8/n

We tried mapping the shifts in differential aging to more specific age windows across chronological age. It becomes a bit tricky but we did find several age windows within both sexes. Could there be sensitive periods in which effects of aging are more pronounced? 7/n https://t.co/q43jfgRPsL

Modeling the interaction between status and age and sex is important as it provides more insights into differential aging patterns. Here for example is differential aging shown across age groups for two DNAm clocks. Note the clock-specific effects too in opposite directionü§î6/n https://t.co/P1Sget99Qt

First take home; individuals diagnosed with scz age differentially as measured by their blood DNAm age than controls. We also observe significant age- and sex-specific effects. 5/n https://t.co/hYSnEfbj7O

We thus set out to investigate this using DNA methylation clocks, which are relatively new tools to study biological aging. We aggregated four European cohorts with blood-based DNAm data available and used three different DNAm clocks to study differential aging. 4/n

Age-related disabilities and morbidities occur at higher prevalence in scz as well. Biological aging has therefore been suggested to be accelerated in scz but without any clear demonstration of altered aging on a molecular level so far. 3/n

Why should we study aging in schizophrenia you ask? Well, people who suffer from scz report higher mortality risk than the general population. They also report decreased life expectancy, i.e. they live on average 15 years shorterüòî 2/n
